    "56205095": {
      "title": "Robust control stability using the error loop",
      "abstract": "This paper formulates the error loop as a tool for designing robust stability control systems in the presence of structured and unstructured uncertainties. The error loop indicates that uncertainties can be accommodated through the design of the noise estimator, which is the unique feedback channel from plant to control. The real-time model that is embedded in the control unit and the noise estimator constitute a state predictor. The embedded model consists of a controllable dynamics plus a disturbance dynamics fed by the noise estimator. It is shown that causality constraint prevents perfect cancellation of causal uncertainties (unknown disturbance), but makes the control law which is fed by the state predictor to play a role, thus offering a further degree of freedom. Employing asymptotic expansions of the closed-loop transfer functions, simple, explicit design formulae derive from stability inequalities. They relate closed-loop eigenvalues to model parameters and requirements, and define an admissible ..."
    }
